      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Return Run with Walking Breaks\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a brisk 3-minute walk to warm up the foot and get the blood moving. No rushing here — this is the most important part of protecting your plantar fascia.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at your easiest, most comfortable effort — the slower end of easy pace (around 6:12/km) is ideal right now. If you feel any foot discomfort, drop immediately to a walk. There is no fitness cost to walking today; there is a real cost to pushing through pain.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk the final 3 minutes. Gentle calf stretches afterward are a great habit for plantar fascia health — check with your physio on any specific stretches they recommend for you.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3-minute brisk walk before any running. Give your plantar fascia and supporting tissues a chance to warm up gradually. If the foot feels stiff or tender during the walk, extend the warmup or skip the run today.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3-minute walk to close out, followed by whatever stretching or mobility work your physiotherapist has prescribed. Do not skip this — the cooldown walk is part of the session.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"James, this first session is all about listening, not performing. Your physiotherapist has cleared you for 20 minutes of easy running, and that ceiling is the plan — not a target to beat. The goal this week is simply to reintroduce running load to the foot without triggering a setback. Your pre-injury fitness (44:00 10K) is still in there; we just need to rebuild the foundation underneath it carefully. Easy pace for you sits between 5:25 and 6:12/km — aim for the slower half of that range right now, roughly 6:00–6:12/km. If your foot speaks up at any point, walk. Walking breaks are not a failure; they are the protocol. Based on your recent weeks (2.4km, 8.5km, 6.1km), your body is already beginning to adapt — that's a really positive sign heading into this week.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Mid-Week Easy Run — Check-In Session\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3-minute walk warmup. Pay close attention to how the foot felt in the 24–48 hours after Tuesday's run. If there was any lingering soreness or stiffness, extend the walk warmup to 5 minutes before attempting any running.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Same easy effort as Tuesday — slow, conversational, and controlled. Think of this as a check-in session: how is the foot responding to the increased load? You should be able to hold a full conversation at this pace. If you cannot, slow down.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3-minute walk cooldown. Note any changes in foot sensation compared to Tuesday — this is useful information for your physio and for adjusting the weekend run.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with a 3-minute walk. If the foot felt fully fine after Tuesday with zero residual soreness, this is a good sign. If there was any morning stiffness (especially those first steps out of bed, which is classic for plantar fasciitis), let your physio know before adding more load.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3 minutes, then complete any physio-prescribed exercises. These are as important as the run itself right now — the rehab work is what rebuilds tissue resilience.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This mid-week session serves two purposes: it gently continues your aerobic base-building and gives you meaningful feedback on how your foot is tolerating the increased volume. Two days of rest between Tuesday and Thursday is intentional — plantar fascia tissue needs adequate recovery time between loading sessions, especially early in a return-to-run process. Stay honest with yourself about how things feel. If Tuesday's run went smoothly with no foot symptoms, this session should feel straightforward. If there was any discomfort, consider replacing this with a 20-minute walk instead — that still counts as productive training and keeps you on track.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Weekend Easy Run — Weekly Capstone\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"5-minute walk warmup for this session — a little longer than the weekday runs since this is the third session of the week and cumulative fatigue in the foot is real. Give it extra time to warm up.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy, relaxed running at 6:00–6:12/km. This is your longest running block of the week — keep the effort well within the easy range. If the foot feels great, resist the urge to go longer or faster. That discipline is what protects your progress.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes to close out the week. This is a good moment to reflect: how did the three sessions feel overall? Any patterns in how the foot responded? That information shapes what we do next week.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Longer walk warmup today — aim for 5 minutes before running. Saturday is your designated long run day, but at this stage 'long' simply means your third session of the week. The cumulative load from Tuesday and Thursday means we cap the running time at 20 minutes total regardless of how good you feel.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5-minute walk, followed by physio exercises. Take a moment to do a genuine foot check: any new pain locations, any increase in symptoms compared to earlier in the week? This is worth noting and sharing with your physiotherapist.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Finishing a three-run week is a meaningful milestone in your return. That consistency — showing up three times, respecting the limits, doing the work — is exactly the kind of process that rebuilds durable fitness. Your total weekly distance this week will land around 10km, which is consistent with your recent training history and well within safe progression. No speed work this week, and none until your physio explicitly clears you for it. Your threshold and interval paces (4:30/km and 4:09/km respectively) will be there when the time is right — right now, the easy pace range is the entire track. Looking ahead: if this week goes well with no foot flare-ups, next week we can begin to explore very gently extending the duration of one session, always staying within physiotherapist guidelines. One week at a time, James — you're building something real here.\",\"perceived_effort\":3}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
